TileMap

TileMap provides a grid to store data

The TileMap node draws textures on a grid, allowing you to paint repeating patterns and design levels efficiently. This approach to creating maps has been widely used in all sorts of 2D games for decades.

In Godot, you can use the TileMap node to draw side-scrolling, top-down, or isometric worlds using the built-in map editor.

Note that the experience creating and using tilesets in Godot 3 can leave a bit to be desired. Itâ€™s perfectly usable even for larger games, but the interface can be a little tedious at times.

Fortunately, the Godot developers are working on it. They hired a developer specifically to redesign the system and interface from scratch.

You can get a glimpse of the redesign here: Tiles editor progress report #3

In this guide, you will learn to:

  • Use autotiles to create a platformerâ€™s background.
  • Use the TileMap nodeâ€™s isometric mode.
  • Make a character die when touching lava floor tiles.
  • Place units on a grid.
  • Occlude 2D lights with the floor.

Setting up a TileMap

A TileMap works as a grid of cells, all of the same size. The first thing to do when creating one is to set the cellsâ€™ size.

You can do so using the Cell -> Size property.

Creating a TileSet resource

By default, all grid cells are empty. You need a TileSet resource to fill cells with tiles.

  1. Click â€œ[empty]â€ on the Tile Set property in the Inspector and create a New TileSet.
  2. Click on the TileSet resource to open the TileSet editor in the bottom panel.
  3. There, click the plus sign and select an image containing tiles.

A tileset is a picture that typically contains many tiling textures, all of the same size.

Hereâ€™s an example from Kenneyâ€™s assets.

Creating a single tile

In Godot 3, you can create three kinds of tiles inside of a TileSet resource:

  • A single tile.
  • An autotile.
  • An atlas tile.

The simplest of the three is a single tile. To create one:

  1. Click New Single Tile in the top right of the TileSet editor.
  2. Click and drag a region over corresponding to the tile in your source image.

Once you created a tile, you can paint it on your TileMap.

To do so:

  1. Select your TileMap node again.

  2. In the vertical tilemap toolbar that appears next to the Inspector, click the tile you want to paint with.

  3. In the toolbar, ensure the paint mode is active by clicking the pencil icon.

  4. Click and drag in the viewport to draw copies of your tile.

Thatâ€™s the absolute basics. To learn more, you can watch our video tutorial dedicated to creating tilesets in Godot: Using the Tileset Editor in Godot 3.1.

Most of it is still relevant as of Godot 3.4.

TileMapâ€™s key features

Here are some key features of the TileMap node.

Collide with 2D physics

TileMap nodes can collide with 2D physics bodies to provide level geometry. They can also make Area2D nodes emit the body_entered signal.

When editing a TileSet, you can add collision shapes to individual tiles:

  1. Click on the tile to edit.
  2. Press 2 to enter collision mode.
  3. Press Shift+R to add a rectangle.
  4. Drag the mouse over the selected tile.

For more complicated tile shapes, you can create a new polygon with Shift+P. This gives you more control over the points of the collision shape.

Once you set the collision shapes, you can set the TileMapâ€™s physics layer by adjusting the Collision -> Layer and Collision -> Mask properties.

Combine multiple tiles into one autotile

Autotiles can change the appearance of a tile based on its surrounding tiles. A common example of dynamically adjusting tiles is in games with road and path-building, like SimCity and Rollercoaster Tycoon:

Game: RollerCoaster Tycoon (1999)

Once set up, you can focus on creating the worldâ€™s geometry without having to rotate or flip any tiles. These next two sections cover how to create an image for Autotiling and set up an Autotile in the TileSet editor.

Creating an Autotile image

To create a tileset prepared for autotiling, you should use a template to make sure your art matches the autotile system.

Setting up an Autotile

Once you created your autotileâ€™s image texture, you can set it up in the TileSet editor.

  1. Click New Autotile, enable snapping, and click anywhere on the image.
  2. In the Inspector, set Snap Options -> Step to match your tilesâ€™ size.
  3. Click and drag on the image again to make the region match the autotile precisely.
  4. In the Inspector, set Selected Tile -> Subtile Size to match the division of tiles on the image.
  5. Set Selected Tile -> Autotile Bitmask Mode to 2x2, 3x3, or 3x3 (minimal) to match the template you used.
  6. Press 5 to enable Bitmask mode.
  7. Click the portions of the subtile to match the red squares that were on the template.

When youâ€™re done setting up the Autotile to match the template, you should have a single Autotile with a bitmask that matches your tileset. The tileset we used for many of our demos uses a 3x3 (minimal) autotile bitmask mode.

If you go back to select your TileMap, you should be able to place one tile and have multiple subtiles of the TileSet appear based on context.

How to use a TileMap in practice

Now weâ€™ll look at some concrete use cases for the TileMap node.

Create stylized platformer levels with autotiles

The autotile system can look at the geometry of your tiles to stylize the corners and edges automatically.

Autotiles save you from creating and placing individual tiles for each corner or edge in a tileset image.

Following the Combine several images into one tile with Autotile section, you can set up autotiles to quickly create and edit platforms that look more authentic to the game world.

Create an isometric dungeon

One of the alternate modes for a TileMap grid is Isometric. This lets you place images with an isometric perspective onto an isometric grid.

Creating an isometric TileMap for flat terrain (where no object can be behind a tile) is similar to creating a regular tileset.

However, introducing collidable walls and props presents some new challenges when creating a tileset:

  • Colliding with isometric walls.
  • Sorting objects in front and behind isometric walls on the tilemap.

When building collision shapes for the wall, we donâ€™t always want to cover the entire wall with collision.

We only care about where the bottom of the wall would touch the ground, using our isometric perspective.

When it comes to sorting objects, the YSort node is a tool of choice.

A YSort node sets the z-index of its children automatically based on their y position. YSort children that are lower on the screen (with a larger y position) will appear in front of their siblings.

In the above example, we never want anything to appear behind the floor, so we leave them in a separate TileMap node.

Only the wall cells and the player need sorting.

To have the TileMap respond to the YSort, enable Cell -> Y Sort. This makes each cell a part of the YSort calculations.

This wonâ€™t always produce successful results for a few reasons:

  • The wall tile: the center of its footprint (where it makes contact with the ground) should match the center of its cell.
  • The player sprite: the center of the playerâ€™s feet should be the origin of the playerâ€™s scene.

For the wall, we fix this by changing the height of the tile using Selected Tile -> Tex Offset in the TileSet editor.

For the player sprite, we align the base of the image with the parent KinematicBody2D controlling its position.

The immediate child of the YSort determines its drawing order.

In the example below, the playerâ€™s child sprite will use the parent IsometricPlayer node, a KinematicBody2D, to determine its drawing order.

React to lava floor tiles

If you want to add hazards to a level using TileMap, youâ€™ll have to determine which tile you hit and how the player should react to different tiles.

The fast way to react to specific tiles is to put all tiles of a certain type (lava, spikes, etc.) on their own TileMap node and place them on a separate physics layer for hazards.

The player can use an Area2D node to detect bodies on that physics layer.

In the example below, we have an Area2D node named HurtBox with its collision mask set to the Lava TileMapâ€™s physics layer.

Note: you can learn more about hit and hurt boxes in the Area2D guide.

First, we connect an Area2D child to our script with a callback function:

onready var _hurt_box: Area2D = $HurtBox
onready var _anim_player_explosion: AnimationPlayer = $AnimationPlayer


func _ready() -> void:
    _hurt_box.connect("body_entered", self, "_on_Area2D_body_entered")

Optionally, if we want to restrict our Area2D to only react to TileMap nodes, we can return from the callback early if the bodyâ€™s class isnâ€™t a TileMap.

To ensure this is the Lava TileMap and not another collider, we can add the TileMap to a node group named Hazards in the Node dock.

We can check the group of the node we hit in code:

func _on_Area2D_body_entered(body: Node) -> void:
    if not body.is_class("TileMap"):
        return
    
    if body.is_in_group("Hazard"):
        _anim_player_explosion.queue("explode")

Another benefit to using a TileMap dedicated to hazards is adding shaders to adjust the look of the tiles on the TileMap.

Here weâ€™ve added a scrolling shader to the Lava TileMap, so it appears more like a liquid:

shader_type canvas_item;

const float SPEED = 0.1;

void fragment(){
    vec2 uv = UV;
    uv.x = 0.501 + mod(uv.x - TIME * SPEED, 0.5);
    COLOR = texture(TEXTURE, uv);
}

Although we used a second TileMap for hazards, you could also use an Area2D instead of a TileMap and use the area_entered signal instead on the playerâ€™s Area2D to detect danger.

You can also use PhysicsServer, Physics2DDirectSpaceState, and Physics2DDirectBodyState to find the tile that the player hit, which would allow reacting to hazards on a single TileMap.

We chose the second TileMap method because it gave us quick access to adjust the materials of one tile, and itâ€™s easier to understand and implement at a glance for other projects.

Place army units on the grid

In strategy games like StarCraft II, youâ€™re able to place units and build structures on a grid.

Placing a building is not only visual; it also adds a new game object that can move and interact with other objects in the world.

Game: StarCraft II (2010)

You can recreate this in 2D using a TileMap, and prevent players from placing units on invalid locations like lakes.

In this example, our TileMap has three potential states per tile:

  • Empty slot.
  • A preview tile showing the unit weâ€™re about to place.
  • An occupied tile that we cannot remove.

We use enumerations to distinguish each tile index that the TileMap is using for these cell states.

These tile indexes are in the TileSet resource. -1 is always an empty cell.

extends Node2D

export var unit_to_instance: PackedScene

enum {
    UNIT_PREVIEW_TILE = 0,
    EMPTY_TILE = -1,
}

# The TileMap is used to show a preview cursor. Used in update_tilemap_preview().
var preview_cursor_position := Vector2.ZERO

# Holds our cursor, as well as other building tiles that already occupy the grid.
onready var tilemap: TileMap = $TileMap

Using _unhandled_input(), you can get the position of the mouse cursor and send it to a function that will pass it to the TileMap:

func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if event is InputEventMouseMotion:
        update_tilemap_preview(event.position)
    
    if event is InputEventMouseButton or event is InputEventScreenTouch:
        if event.pressed:
            create_unit_at(event.position)

We can input a 2D position, send it to the TileMap using world_to_map(), and get a grid-oriented position out using map_to_world().

This gives us a position to place a new ship on the grid.

## Places a PackedScene, with its position snapped to the TileMap.
func create_unit_at(coordinates: Vector2) -> void:
    # Snap input coordinates to the TileMap.
    var map_position := tilemap.world_to_map(coordinates)
    var selected_tile := tilemap.get_cellv(map_position)
    # If update_tilemap_preview() didn't put the cursor here, don't put a unit here either.
    if selected_tile != UNIT_PREVIEW_TILE:
        return
    var new_unit := unit_to_instance.instance()
    # Get a world position out of the map so our unit placement matches the grid.
    new_unit.position = tilemap.map_to_world(map_position)
    add_child(new_unit)

We can also fill the TileMap with a preview tile to show where we will place a unit.

We can take coordinates passed from _unhandled_input() and call get_cellv() on the TileMap to determine if the cell is empty or not.

## Updates the preview cursor, checks if it would overlap an already-occupied tile.
func update_tilemap_preview(coordinates: Vector2) -> void:
    # Don't show the preview over an existing tile.
    if tilemap.get_cellv(tilemap.world_to_map(coordinates)) != EMPTY_TILE:
        return
    # Empty the previous cursor position.
    tilemap.set_cellv(preview_cursor_position, EMPTY_TILE)
    # Update the cursor position.
    preview_cursor_position = tilemap.world_to_map(coordinates)
    # Use the cursor position to place the unit preview tile.
    tilemap.set_cellv(preview_cursor_position, UNIT_PREVIEW_TILE)

With the unit creation script done, now itâ€™s up to us to determine what to put in it.

We went for a ship that slowly moves and disappears after enough time has passed, but instancing any other scene would work just as well:

func _ready() -> void:
    # The "Die" animation calls queue_free() on this node.
    _timer.connect("timeout", _anim_player, "play", ["Die"])


func _physics_process(_delta: float) -> void:
    var velocity = _direction * SPEED
    move_and_slide(velocity)

Your questions

How do I make my TileMap collide with the player?

Add a collision shape to each tile youâ€™re using.

If youâ€™re using autotiles, you can assign collision shapes to each subtile.

Make sure that the collision shape is convex. If it becomes concave, press the Make Concave button in the tileset editor.

Whatâ€™s the difference between a single tile and an autotile?

A single tile interprets the exact region set in the TileSet editor as the entire tile.

Meanwhile, the region of an Autotile can be an image with multiple tiles.

The appearance of each cell using the autotile changes depending on its surrounding cells. Two things determine the appearance of an autotile:

  • Bitmask - refer to Setting up an Autotile.
  • Icon - how the tile appears in the palette, or when thereâ€™s no correct bitmask setting for the current state of surrounding tiles.

How do I randomize the placement of tiles?

Use an autotile and make the tiles you want to appear randomly have matching bitmasks.

When multiple subtiles use the same bitmask, the node will randomly choose between those subtiles when the corresponding tile geometry appears in the TileMap.

You can make tiles appear more often than others by pressing 6 to edit the subtileâ€™s Priority.

If you want to randomize the placement of single tiles, you can also write a script that randomly picks from the available set of tiles:

_tilemap.set_cell(0, 0, randi() % NUMBER_OF_TILES)

You can watch our free tutorial covering the topic of procedural map generation - Intro to GDScript 2: Procedural Map Generation Tutorial on YouTube.

Troubleshooting

When running the game, there are gaps between my tiles

Game engines draw tiles in such a way visual artifacts can appear.

This happens pretty much regardless of the engine:

  • When smoothly panning the view.
  • When zooming the view in and out.

The reason it happens is the graphics cards using different strategies to sample pixels of your source texture and map it to the screen, which can cause it to sample a pixel from a neighboring tile. We call this bleeding and it also happens with 3D objects.

The definitive fix to this requires to design tile set images with a few pixels between each tile texture.

Ideally, you want each tile to have a border around it that replicates the tileâ€™s pixels. This gets rid of all artifacts.

Godotâ€™s TileSet editor offers snapping options to take that into account when drawing regions around tiles.

Lastly, for a quick but incomplete fix, you can try the following project settings:

  • Rendering -> 2d -> Snapping -> Use Gpu Pixel Snap. This works well for pixel art games but makes you lose smoothness when panning the game view.
  • Rendering -> Batching -> Precision -> Uv Contract. This can prevent visual gaps but also slightly squash the border of your textures.

You can use both settings together. They come in handy for game jams, prototypes, demos, and may also do the job for games with flat art styles, like our tower defense demo.

The TileMap wonâ€™t collide with the player

Check the physics layers of your TileMap and your player.

Check that collision shapes are set on the tiles youâ€™re using.

If some collision shapes work, but others donâ€™t, make sure any concave shapes have Make Concave set and appear purple in the tileset editor.
